Madagascar has numerous endemic plants and animals, and a recent update to the endemic flora reported that 84% of indigenous angiosperms are endemic to the island, underscoring the critical role of the island in retaining this genetic repository of the world’s flora (
Callmander et al. 2011
). Land degradation is a major problem on the island despite many initiatives to protect the unique key ecosystems present. These include establishing, augmenting, and managing protected areas ( Moat and Smith 2007 ) as well as finding methods to enrich and replant native tree species (
Ramanankierana et al. 2013
).

The primary objectives of the study reported in this paper were to describe the distribution and ecology of dictyostelids on Madagascar , an island characterized by one of the most unique biotas of the world, and to compare and contrast the assemblage of species present (especially members of the genus
Heterostelium
) with those reported from other regions of the world.

The 52 samples were not equally productive for dictyostelids. No isolates were recovered from sixteen of the samples processed, but dictyostelids were recorded from 17 of the 18 localities. In only two instances did the number of clones recorded for a single collecting site exceed 100, and in only two others did the number of clones exceed 50. A total of 401 clones were recovered from the positive samples, for an average of 193 clones/gram for all samples (
Fig. 14
). For dictyostelids, a clone is considered to be derived from a single propagule (spore or microcyst) and thus represents as much of an “individual” as possible to recognize for this group of microorganisms.

The results obtained in the present study appear to provide additional information relating to the importance of environmental factors on the distribution of dictyostelids in nature. In Costa Rica (
Landolt et al. 2014
), the only samples which did not yield dictyostelids were either from high elevations or very xeric sites. In Mexico (Cavender et al. 2010), only samples collected from several desert sites did not produce dictyostelids. In Madagascar , with a much smaller number of samples, dictyostelid density in the processed samples was 193 clones/gram and 3.9 clones/isolation culture plate. This compares with 165 clones/gram for Costa Rica and 229/gram for Mexico .As already indicated, there were 30 described species plus four unidentified species isolated in the present study. This is a relatively high number, since there were 26 described species for all of Costa Rica and 28 for Mexico , which were sampled more extensively. The xeric and mesic sites in Madagascar had equal levels of species richness, with 17 and 18 species, respectively.

Despite the dry environmental conditions that prevail throughout most of Madagascar , species richness of dictyostelids was greater than all areas of the African mainland sampled to date. For example, there were 13 described species from tropical forests of the Central African Republic (
Cavender et al. 1993
), 10 from both Kenya and South Africa (Cavender et al. 2010), and a total of 25 for all of mainland Africa. In this initial sampling of Madagascar , there were 13 described species along with17 new, previously undescribed species.

Interestingly, some similarities also have been noted for the myxomycetes, another entirely different group of eumycetozoans, from Madagascar and arid areas of Mexico (
Wrigley de Basanta et al. 2013
). It is possible that longdistance dispersal may have been a factor, since a recent study (
Stephenson et al. 2019
) reported the occurrence in the Namib Desert of southern Africa of several species of myxomycetes previously known only from the New World. However, long-distance dispersal does not appear to be a factor for dictyostelids since their spores do not ordinarily become airborne ( Stephenson and Landolt 1992 ).
